<article>
    <h1>Com&#xAD;mu&#xAD;nity sol&#xAD;i&#xAD;dar&#xAD;ity</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201220/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-20"><time>2020-12-20</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ong Sor Fern</span>
    </section>

    <p>When the pan­demic hit early this year, the arts com­mu­nity re­dis­cov­ered a sense of sol­i­dar­ity, band­ing to­gether to sup­port free­lance mem­bers who lost gigs and in­come, and ini­ti­at­ing un­prece­dented col­lab­o­ra­tions to help one an­other through the hard times.</p>
    <p>For the first time, theatre com­pa­nies got to­gether to of­fer tick­et­ing discounts.</p>
    <p>In Fe­bru­ary, af­ter the Gov­ern­ment raised the disease out­break re­sponse sys­tem con­di­tion to orange, the Sin­ga­pore Reper­tory Theatre (SRT), Pangde­mo­nium and Wild Rice an­nounced a dis­count scheme to en­cour­age pa­trons to at­tend their shows. Those who bought tick­ets for SRT’s The Life­span Of A Fact, Pangde­mo­nium’s The Son or Wild Rice’s The Im­por­tance Of Be­ing Earnest re­ceived a 15 per cent dis­count for tick­ets to the other shows.</p>
    <p>SRT’s di­rec­tor Char­lotte Nors says: “Our sol­i­dar­ity dis­count helped all three com­pa­nies reach a dif­fer­ent au­di­ence and showed how we were able to col­lab­o­rate and sup­port one an­other.”</p>
    <p>The sup­port, she says, was more im­por­tant than ac­tual sales.</p>
    <p>That ini­tial part­ner­ship turned into an artis­tic one too, when the com­pa­nies’ artis­tic di­rec­tors got to­gether to shoot The Pitch, a short film di­rected and co-scripted by Ken Kwek. The laugh-out-loud­funny film raised about $127,000.</p>
    <p>Vet­eran fund-raiser Pasar Glam­our Art Aid, founded by theatre vet­er­ans Jan­ice Koh, Pet­rina Kow and Pam Oei, di­rected its at­ten­tion to the many arts free­lancers hit by venue clo­sures. Some 147 arts work­ers each re­ceived $500 grants to help with bills.</p>
    <p>Even free­lancers them­selves stepped up to help.</p>
    <p>Ad­junct lec­turer and free­lance writer Ng Swee San drew from her sav­ings to com­mis­sion artists to cre­ate small projects, of­fer­ing en­cour­age­ment and work to var­i­ous free­lancers.</p>
    <p>On Face­book, the SG Covid-19 Cre­ative/Cul­tural Pro­fes­sion­als & Free­lancers Sup­port Group page shared in­for­ma­tion about nav­i­gat­ing bu­reau­cracy and var­i­ous job op­por­tu­ni­ties.</p>
    <p>Theatre com­pa­nies have also turned their at­ten­tion to groom­ing young tal­ent dur­ing the cri­sis.</p>
    <p>The Nec­es­sary Stage’s Play­wrights Cove, T:>Works’ 24-Hour Play­writ­ing Com­pe­ti­tion and Wild Rice’s Di­rec­tors’ Res­i­dency Pro­gramme showed the es­tab­lished groups’ com­mit­ment to the next gen­er­a­tion of prac­ti­tion­ers.</p>

